				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${CH}_{4}+{H}_{2}O\to CO+3{H}_{2}$$\end{document}

In typical industrial applications targeting H2 generation via this pathway, a second reaction also occurs, producing additional hydrogen through the water gas shift (WGS) reactor. In this case, CO and water react, producing hydrogen and carbon dioxide, as in reaction (2):2CO+H2O→CO2+H2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
